I don&#39;t like the decision made by the Java library team to leave out the case of a no-parameter-no-return-value `Function` interface, and nudging those who need one to use `Runnable`. I think it inaccurately, and even incorrectly, redirects attention and subsequent assumptions when trying to read through a code base. Especially years after the original code was written.

Given communication and readability are far higher concerns for me and my audiences, I have composed a small helper `interface` designed and named in the spirit of the Java library&#39;s missing case:

```java
@FunctionalInterface
public interface VoidSupplier {
  void get();
}
```

And in my case, the likelihood of an Exception being thrown in the method is considerably higher, so I actually added a checked exception like this:

```java
@FunctionalInterface
public interface VoidSupplier {
  void get() throws Exception;
}
```


